        <td width="73%" align="left" valign="top" style="padding-top:5px; padding-bottom:5px;"><span style="text-align:justify;">Obstructive Sleep Apnea Syndrome (OSA) is a life threatening disorder affecting over 18 million Americans.Research estimates that up to 9% of adult males and 4% of females suffer from sleep disordered breathing, yet fewer than 10% have been diagnosed. In fact, the most recent studies have shown that 1 in 4 adults in the United States (31% of all men and 21% of all women over 18) are at &quot;high risk&quot; for OSA (based on analysis of the National Sleep Foundation's 2005 Sleep in America survey).Furthermore 40% of Americans snore and 40% of snorers have OSA with no signs or symptoms of the disease</span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td colspan="2" align="left" valign="top">Serious consequences of untreated OSA include:<br />
<ol start="1" type="1">
  <li>Increased risk of stroke</li>
  <li>Increased high blood pressure</li>
  <li>Increased risk of diabetes</li>
  <li>Poor memory and other cognitive impairments</li>
  <li>Male impotence and decreased sex drive</li>
  <li>Headaches</li>
  <li>Increased risk of motor vehicle accidents</li>
  <li>Increase in Gastrointestinal Reflux Disease (GERD)</li>
  <li>Increase in ADHD in children</li>
  <li>Death</li>
</ol>
<p>If you are a physician treating these disorders and symptoms  then many of your patients may have underlying sleep disorder breathing (Obstructive  Sleep Apnea or upper airway resistance).</p>
<div style="text-align:center; padding-bottom:8px;"><a href="about_sleep_apnea.php" class="click">Click here to learn more about Obstructive Sleep Apnea</a></div></td>
        </tr>
    </table>    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td align="left" valign="top"><p>Dental Sleep Solutions&reg; can help!  Our goal is to work closely with other medical professionals to provide comprehensive treatment for patients suffering from these serious disorders.  Our DSS dentists have all received specialty training in dental sleep medicine and are committed to a team approach in the treatment of sleep problems.  We will work with you to insure our patients have the best care available.  If you have a patient that is suffering from Obstructive Sleep Apnea, upper airway resistance or is troubled by snoring, then Dental Sleep Solutions&reg; can help!  According to the American Academy of Sleep Medicine's 2005 Practice Parameters, patients with mild to moderate OSA or any patient who cannot tolerate CPAP should be given the option of a Dental Sleep Device. <a href="#" class="page">Click here to see Practice Parameters</a>.</p>
      <div style="text-align:center; padding-bottom:8px;"><a href="#" class="click"> Click here to learn more about treating sleep apnea with dental sleep devices.</a></div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td align="left" valign="top"><p>Our DSS dentists are committed to our high standards and rigid protocols for treatment.  If you have a patient that you would like to refer to one of our offices we will be happy to see them for a free consultation to evaluate if they are a good candidate for Dental Device Therapy.  Throughout their treatment you will be part of the process and will be kept informed of your patient's progress.  During the process you will be given multiple written updates to help you track your patient's success.  This written correspondence will not only keep you informed, it will serve as the proper medical documentation needed to defer your liability for untreated Obstructive Sleep Apnea patients.
